# Run long-running tinderbox-ng jobs inside `screen`

ALWAYS launch long-running drivers — `tinderbox-ng continue`,
`compare-matrix.sh`, `tinderbox-matrix` — inside a detached `screen`
session on the VM. NEVER use `continue --background` / `nohup setsid` for
these.

Why: a `screen` session gives a single top-level process whose tree can be
killed cleanly in one shot. Detached/`nohup setsid` runs reparent their
compare workers to init (`ppid=1`), so stopping them degenerates into
pattern-killing individual build processes (`pkill -f cc1plus`, …) — which
is error-prone and risks shooting unrelated processes.

## Launch (preferred)

```sh
ssh root@vm-linux.local screen -dmS tinderbox-ng \
    tinderbox-ng continue --jobs 16
# reattach:
ssh -t root@vm-linux.local screen -r tinderbox-ng
```

## Stop cleanly (one shot, no random kills)

```sh
ssh root@vm-linux.local screen -S tinderbox-ng -X quit   # kills the whole tree
# verify:
ssh root@vm-linux.local 'ps -eo pid,args | grep -E "compare-matrix|sbin/tinderbox-ng comp" | grep -v grep | wc -l'
```

## Never

- Don't `pkill -f "<pattern that appears in your own command>"` — it
  self-matches and kills your SSH shell.
- Don't kill build tools (`cc1plus`, `ninja`, `emerge`, …) by name to stop a
  run. Kill the `screen` session instead.
